    <a href="/reading/theory-of-computation/" class="text-sm mb-4 inline-block">&larr; back to Theory of Computation</a>

    <h1>Context-Free Grammars</h1>
    <p class="text-gray-400 text-sm mb-6">Maheshwari &amp; Smid &middot; Ch. 4 &middot; <a href="https://cglab.ca/~michiel/TheoryOfComputation/">Introduction to Theory of Computation</a></p>

    <div class="bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg p-5 mb-8 callout">
      <p class="text-lg" style="max-width:none">A <strong>context-free grammar</strong> (CFG) generates strings through production rules. Each rule rewrites a single variable into a sequence of variables and terminals. CFGs describe more languages than regular expressions: they can handle nesting, matching brackets, and recursive structure.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- Productions and derivations -->
    <h3>Productions and derivations</h3>
    <p>A CFG is a 4-tuple (V, &Sigma;, R, S):</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>V</strong> &mdash; finite set of variables (nonterminals)</li>
      <li><strong>&Sigma;</strong> &mdash; finite set of terminals (the alphabet)</li>
      <li><strong>R</strong> &mdash; production rules of the form A &rarr; w</li>
      <li><strong>S</strong> &mdash; start variable (S &isin; V)</li>
    </ul>
    <p>A <strong>derivation</strong> is a sequence of rule applications starting from S that produces a string of terminals.</p>

    <!-- SVG: Parse tree for 1+2*3 -->
    <h3>Parse trees</h3>
    <p>A parse tree shows the structure of a derivation. The root is the start variable. Internal nodes are variables. Leaves are terminals. Reading the leaves left-to-right gives the derived string.</p>

    <div class="flex justify-center my-6">
